defaultI welcome the opportunity to contribute to the Home Affairs Select Committee’s second inquiry into Police and Crime Commissioners.   My submission is based around my own experience as a Police and Crime Commissioner in the areas the Committee has indicated it intends to address.  
default&#xa0;defaultThe effectiveness of Commissioners in reducing crime and delivering an effective police servicedefault&#xa0;
default2)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn Cheshire, I have been working closely with the Chief Constable and his senior leadership team to prevent and reduce crime.  Since the introduction of my Police and Crime Plan in April 2013, there have been over 1,000 fewer victims of crime in Cheshire and a 16% reduction in the number of re-offenders.  In September 2013, the Constabulary recorded the lowest volume of crimes for many years and victim satisfaction with the overall service received has increased to 89%, the fourth highest nationally.   
default 
defaultI have also robustly challenged the Chief Constable in areas where I believe there is a need for improvement.  For instance, I ha
defaultd
default some concern regarding the rate of detections for bur
defaultglary dwelling offences and
default commissioned HMIC to conduct a formal rev
defaultiew of
default burglary investigations.
default  As a result of this
default,
default the Constabulary introduced more rigour to the process which has positively contributed to the crime and detection figures.
default&#xa0;
default3)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultI have worked with the Constabulary to introduce strategies which tackle issues highlighted within my 
defaultPolice and Crime 
defaultPlan, for instance a Mental Health Strategy and a Rural, Heritage and Wildlife Crime Strategy. 
defaultThe Mental Health Strategy will increase the confidence and skills of front line officers in dealing with mental health incidents and use this information with the health service, Mental Health Trusts and local authority partners to develop better pathways to help individuals with mental health needs. For those with acute needs, the focus is on ensuring that they are assessed in appropriate places of safety, particularly when under the influence of alcohol and drugs.  The Rural Crime Strategy will ensure that an effective, efficient and proportionate response is provided to crimes and incidents affecting rural communities and Cheshire’s wildlife and heritage assets.
